West Nile virus, human case - USA (New York) 20000804.1303
[1
Date: Mon, 23 Jul 2001 18:00:42 -0400
From: Steven_Wiersma@doh.state.fl.us

The Florida Department of Health (FDOH) has identified the first
*presumptive* human case of West Nile virus (WNV) in Florida. The
patient developed acute encephalitis in mid-July. Analysis of the
patient's serum showed a positive IgM antibody test to WNV. FDOH
expects to have results of additional laboratory tests later this
week. The patient lives in Madison County, Florida. Madison County has
reported 4 birds which tested positive for WNV. Madison County is
adjacent to Jefferson County, where WNV has been found in 5 birds and
in 1 horse.
Because of the increased activity of Eastern equine encephalitis and
the WNV activity, a medical alert that was issued last month for
Holmes, Washington and Jackson counties has been extended to include
Bay, Calhoun, Gulf, Franklin, Liberty, Gadsden, Wakulla, Leon,
Jefferson, Madison and Taylor counties.
A copy of the press release issued on 23 Jul 2001 by FDOH may be found
at:
<http://www.doh.state.fl.us/disease_ctrl/epi/alerts/alerts.htm>
